         <abstract>
            <p>Assuming that a fund manager is primarily concerned with the welfare of those who ultimately receive the gains or losses, how should he decide on the fund's risk level? On its division among broad asset classes such as common stocks and bonds? On the proper degree of diversification? Answers to these questions based on casual intuition are giving way to answers based on modern capital theory.</p>
          </abstract>
